@node OVERVIEW " Overview "

@{b}@{u} Overview @{ub}@{uu}

For the last 8 months I've been involved in designing and implementing an
innovative rescheduling algorithm (maybe someone will use it on a PowerPC
OS - hope WarpOS, Sam...;) ) and have always loved OSes for their simple
complexity, thus learnt lots of stuff about scheduling and kernels in general.
All this interest probably was dued to the charm that Executive by Petri
Nordlund had on me since I first installed it: the best OS enhancer, in my
opinion.
Nevertheless, studying existing OSes' schedulers (NT, UNIX/Linux, BeOS, AmigaOS
powered by Executive) and facing problems on my skin, I realized that Executive
has kind of a lack: catched processes are not treated according to their original
priority. And since every AmigaOS program is designed to run on a fixed
priority round-robin scheduler, special attention should be kept for original
priorities, giving rescheduled tasks a sort of dynamic order, someway.
fIXnICE achieves this goal forcing a nice value computed in function of the
original priority, implemented with both some exec library patches and realtime
services done by a resident fIXnICE (read the @{" usage " link USAGE} chapter for details
about fIXnICE abilities).
Basically, fIXnICE is an Executive client that calculates a nice in the
range -20..20 (the range supported by Executive and most UNIX systems) for each
process, in proportion to the real priority, that is kind of an "importance"
the task has been designed for.
With fIXnICE, having a full dynamic OS will be possible, since processes won't
be kept all at the same scheduling privileges, and with a lower nice value,
urgent tasks will both respond better and be kept on a high priority feedback
queue (assuming you configured Executive to use the feedback algorithm - the
rescheduler which fIXnICE has been coded to work at its best with).
Though, a full dynamic OS is only an extreme example, and I would
discourage it (certain system servers has been thought to run ALWAYS at the
highest priority, not for pre-emption troubles but for performance and response
reasons - such as input.device or Executive itself), even if the computer
would be anyway highly usable for most "light" applications, and moreover you
won't suffer by scheduling deadlocks anymore, such as crashed device drivers or
busy-waiting shells.
Anyway, an almost-full dynamic enviroment would be realstic, that is
rescheduling most processes, leaving out only either bugged-programs (which
won't like being pre-empted or rescheduled) or really urgent tasks.

A powerful configuration which would let you taste the shiver of a superior OS
could be the following...;)
Set Executive catch range from a very low bound, which could be -100 for
example, to a quite high bound for AmigaOS, maybe 5-10 (including most shells
and DOS drivers) or even 11-12 (even high priority exec devices like scsi.device
for IDE HDs and cybppc.device for Ultra-Wide-SCSI HDs - not guarateed to work
everywhere: data loss may occur depending on the device implementation and on
your 68k CPU).
Then set the dynamic range (that is the priority range where all catched
processes will be rescheduled) to something like -80..-10 or anyway a quite
large range BELOW zero.
Theoretically, you might set the dynamic range also on positive priorities
(AmigaOS internal scheduler just sorts queued tasks, and if the highest one is
at -50 or 80 has no difference: it will be run as first), but since few
processes really need to be kept at fixed priority, which will obviously be a
positive value - otherwise what would they be kept fixed for ? -, it would led
to conflicts.
Now start fIXnICE from your startup-sequence (even before launching Executive:
it will wait for it and then start working) with @{" MINPRI " link USAGE} at -30 or so and
@{" MAXPRI " link USAGE} at catch range's higher bound or lower: processes with priority 0
will get nice 0, priority with negative values higher than -30 (or so) will be
a proportional nice value between 1 and 19 (or 20, depending on the @{" OFFRANGE " link USAGE}
switch, and positive priorities will become nices in the range -1..-19 (or -20,
as for positive nices).
Processes outside fIXnICE range will get nice 20 or -20 in case their original
priority is negative or positive, respectively.
Every process will get a nice, but only dynamic ones will be affected by it: it
would have caused too overhead checking if the process is reschedulable or not,
and it wouldn't have been useful.

What else to say...try it, probably experimenting will make you realize the
best setting for your ideal envirment.
I would appreciate @{" feedback " link FEEDBACK} about particularly efficient configurations.

Have fun ! :)

@endnode


@node HISTORY " History "

@{b}@{u} History @{ub}@{uu}

@{b}v1.1@{ub}    - promised @{" NICEZERO " link USAGE} feature giving a certain nice value to
          processes with priority 0, and offsetting proportional nices from it.
        - patch-and-leave mode still not avaiable - wait folks, it's not so
          easy as it could seem :)
        - CTRL-F signal service changed to something much more useful: it
          toggles patches ON/OFF, thus allowing you to load bugging programs
          such as CrossDOS by just turning OFF patches for a moment.
        - super-secret hidden part finally fixed: find it !
        - the guide file has been fixed: USAGE section doc said that signal
          services worked in REFRESH mode, but that's not true :P

@{b}v1.0@{ub}    - first public version
        - patch-and-leave mode not avaiable yet.
        - CTRL-F signal service absolutely useless ;)
        - due to a (mysterious) bug, the super-secret hidden part didn't work on
          the spread version...shame on me :|

@endnode


@node TODO " To do "

@{b}@{u} To do @{ub}@{uu}

fIXnICE is far from being finished or perfect.
I think only time and various testers (with different needs and habits) will
signal possible improvements, fixes and new features to implement.
However, mainly 4 features could be added soon as probably useful:

  - a sort of user-definable @{b}function@{ub} or @{b}proportional factor@{ub} for both
    positive and negative nices would make fIXnICE even more flexible and would
    let assigning a kind of non-linear step to nice calculation, distancing for
    example high-priority tasks nices more than default.

  - the @{b}patch-and-leave@{ub} mode, i.e. @{" RESIDENT " link USAGE} switch won't be compulsory,
    as it had been designed to be, allowing a patch-only version of fIXnICE
    without keeping idle (=dirty) tasks alive (though, excluding all realtime
    services).

  - maybe a @{b}commodity@{ub} spirit for resident mode, in order to make fIXnICE
    active, inactive and removed in a standard and OS-compliant way.

  - making signal services avaiable also in refresh mode.

Let me know...

@endnode

@node USAGE " Usage "

@{b}@{u} Usage @{ub}@{uu}

Try to run fIXnICE with a "?" as argument, and you'll get the template.
Thought it may appear complicated, it is really like this :)
fIXnICE job is always the same (calculating nice values instead in function of
fixed priorities given to processes), but it has several additional options
and operating modes, most of them designed to help user to set both fIXnICE and
Executive well for his needs.

Here's a full explaination of all fIXnICE options:

     @{b}MINPRI@{ub}           this keyword specifies the lower bound for nice
                      calculation, that is the highest nice value will
                      be given to processes having this priority (or even
                      lower). You can set this parameter to the lower bound
                      of the catch range in Executive configuration, or to
                      a value you know there shouldn't be processes with
                      a lower priority.
                      Usually, it should be higher or equal than Executive
                      catch range lower bound.
                      @{u}Remember that MINPRI can't be higher or equal than 0 !@{uu}

                      @{i}example 1  @{ui}
                      if your Executive prefs are set to a lower catch range
                      of -100 (processes lower than -100 will be kept to their
                      low fixed priority), and fIXnICE @{u}MINPRI@{uu} is -30,
                      then processes with priority lower than -30 will get
                      nice 20 (if @{u}OFFRANGE@{uu} is on), or processes with
                      priority lower or equal than -30 will get nice 20 (if
                      @{u}OFFRANGE@{uu} is off). Other processes with priority
                      lower than 0 and higher than -30 will get a positive nice
                      value proportionally -29..0 -> 19..0

                      @{i}example 2  @{ui}
                      if Executive catch range lower bound is equal to fIXnICE
                      @{u}MINPRI@{uu}, then all positive nice values will be proportional
                      and there will be no dynamic processes with nice 20, if
                      @{u}OFFRANGE@{uu} is specified.


     @{b}MAXPRI@{ub}           this parameter is analogous to @{u}MINPRI@{uu}, but it refers
                      to higher bounds, and thus negative nice value.
                      @{u}Notice that MAXPRI value can't be lower or equal than 0 !@{uu}

                      @{i}example 1  @{ui}
                      if Executive higher catch range is set to 10 (watch out:
                      also DOS devices and some exec devices will be rescheduled),
                      you may set fIXnICE @{u}MAXPRI@{ui} to 10 without @{u}OFFRANGE@{uu},
                      thus such system servers will get nice -20.

                      @{i}example 2  @{ui}
                      if your want to try a full dynamic-priority OS (fIXnICE has been
                      created also for this purpose), you could set Executive catch
                      range from -120 to 120, for example, and rescheduling range
                      from -50 to 30, or from -70 to -10 if you want to exclude
                      some high-pri tasks from being rescheduled; then, use fIXnICE
                      with @{u}MAXPRI@{uu}=20 and @{u}MINPRI@{uu}=-30 with @{u}OFFRANGE@{uu} on,
                      thus giving -19 nice to all common processes till "input.device"
                      system server, and all (if any) processes over 20 will get
                      -20 nice, as urgent.
                      NOTE: my suggestion would be keeping "input.device" at
                      fixed priority anyway by excluding it in Executive prefs.


     @{b}REFRESH@{ub}          this key must specify the refresh rate in seconds, i.e. the
                      time between every nice recalculation of every process in
                      the system (both ready and waiting queues).
                      At every refresh all existing processes are forced to be
                      rescheduled and nice values are forced to values computed
                      from their real priority, thus deleting any nice value manually
                      changed by the user.
                      It's very useful for processes that have used the CPU for less
                      than a quantum and then have fallen asleep: Executive keeps such
                      tasks at their original fixed priority until they use the CPU
                      a bit more. This side effect generates the need of setting
                      Executive catch range below 0, otherwise sleeping tasks won't
                      get the CPU at awake if their pri is around 0, because the high
                      feedback queue will keep most processes much higher than 0.
                      The refresh option has been mainly implemented for those
                      who have troubles with fIXnICE patches, thus using a refresh of
                      3 seconds or so, together with @{u}NOPATCH@{uu} will let you
                      enjoy a fIXnICEed OS without bugs dued to lame programs that
                      doesn't like the new AddTask() (see the @{" known bugs " link BUGS} section
                      for details).
                      @{u}This option obviously needs the RESIDENT switched on, but signal@{uu}
                      @{u}services (except CTRL-C that quits) won't work ! !@{uu}


     @{b}RESIDENT@{ub}         it will keep fIXnICE as a resident process, and will not
                      make it patch and quit (it's not a commodity, anyway !).
                      @{u}To keep fIXnICE resident you have to launch it with a Run@{uu}
                      @{u}command, for example if you start fIXnICE from startup-sequence,@{uu}
                      @{u}otherwise the Shell process will become fIXnICE and startup@{uu}
                      @{u}won't go on !@{uu}
                      Keeping fIXnICE as a resident process has, besides the disadvantage
                      of having another idle task in the system (a sense of dirtyness), some
                      bonus features: the process will be completely idle (unless a @{u}REFRESH@{uu}
                      value is specified), but it will do some services on signals.
                      As always, CTRL-C (signal 12) will make fIXnICE quit and restore
                      system vectors as they were when it performed the patch (be aware !).
                      A CTRL-E (signal 14) will make fixnice perform a refresh (just like
                      the one performed at startup and at every refresh timeout, if any).
                      A CTRL-F (signal 15) will make fixnice toggle patches, in order to
                      make a bugging program loadable just disabling the patches before
                      running it, and enabling them again afterwards.
                      @{i}WARNING !!! The non-resident mode has not been implemented yet
                                  till this fIXnICE version, thus the @{u}RESIDENT @{uu}
                                  switch has to be always specified, otherwise an error
                                  will occur.  
                                  However, fIXnICE code has already been designed to
                                  support a patch-and-quit mode, that will be hopefully
                                  implemented in the next few versions (if you strongly
                                  need it, give me some @{" feedback " link FEEDBACK}).  @{ui}


     @{b}NOPATCH@{ub}          simply will prevent fIXnICE from patching system vectors.
                      It shouldn't be useful, since fIXnICE power is mostly in patching
                      exec thus every new process or priority change will get the correct
                      nice value.
                      Anyway, it may be used together with @{u}REFRESH@{uu} if fIXnICE
                      patches give you troubles with some programs (read the @{" known bugs " link BUGS} section).
                      Or it could be used alone just exploit the break signals services
                      provided by fIXnICE when resident.
                      @{u}Obviously the RESIDENT switch must be set, otherwise it won't@{uu}
                      @{u}make much sense avoid patching and then quitting...@{uu} :)

     @{b}SHOOT@{ub}            this option is for those who hate fIXnICE and its bugs :)
                      It will simply run fIXnICE once, performing a single refresh on
                      existing processes, without patching or anything.
                      You could use it, for example, just to force every task into the
                      rescheduling range (read the @{u}REFRESH@{uu} explaination about
                      Executive pseudo-bug), with the "side effect" of updating all
                      nices to correct values depending on their real priorities
                      (after all, fIXnICE has been done just for this :) If you think
                      a shoot mode without recalculating nices would be useful, let
                      me know...)
                      @{u}Guess what ? It can't be used together with the RESIDENT arg...@{uu}

     @{b}OFFRANGE@{ub}         this damned option is more complicated to be explained
                      than to be used...
                      Briefly, it affects nice calculation at @{u}MINPRI@{uu} and
                      @{u}MAXPRI@{uu} bounds: if it's on, only processes outside
                      fIXnICE range will get nice -20 or 20, others inside the
                      range will be from -19 to 19.
                      It's useful with reschedulers that treats min/max nices as
                      special cases, but could be anyway useful in certain situations.
                      Read the @{u}MINPRI@{uu} and @{u}MAXPRI@{uu} explaination
                      to see examples of how and when to use it.

     @{b}NICEZERO@{ub}         this feature is new in version 1.1.
                      The value specified by @{u}NICEZERO@{uu} will be given to
                      every process with priority 0, and other priorities will
                      be proportionally computed with the usual technique but
                      positive and negative nice ranges will change.
                      Experimenting with this feature is the best way to choose a suitable
                      nice calculation for the own needs.
                      @{u}Notice that the allowed range is -18..18 for OFFRANGE reasons. @{uu}
                      @{i}Be careful with this option since reschedulers act differently @{ui}
                      @{i}to positive nice values ! System performace loss may occur !  @{ui}

                      @{i}example  @{ui}
                      if @{u}MINPRI@{uu}=-30, @{u}MAXPRI@{uu}=10 and @{u}NICEZERO@{uu}=5
                      then processes at priority 0 will get nice 5, negative processes
                      will get nices 19..6 (19 or 20, depending on @{u}OFFRANGE@{uu}) and
                      positive processes will get nice 4..-20.
@endnode

@node REQ " Requirements "

@{b}@{u} Requirements @{ub}@{uu}

Well, if you've already read how it works, what do you think you need ?
Briefly:

 - an Amiga without fIXnICE already installed
 - an Executive version that doesn't do fIXnICE job :)
 - an editor where to modify your startup-sequence
 - lots of CPU-bound processes to see how fIXnICE works
 - a 68020 or better (I'm not going to support 68000 at all, since I'm even
   considering to support only superpipelined or superscalar processors)

@endnode

@node INSTALL " Installation "

@{b}@{u} Installation @{ub}@{uu}

I told you: copy it to c: !
Did you think I was joking, or ?!

@endnode

@node FEEDBACK " Feedback "

@{b}@{u} Feedback @{ub}@{uu}

Since I don't know if this program would really improve average performance on
every machine and enviroment, I would appreciate both enthusiastic mails by fans
and (probably more sincere) mails by disgusted people puking because of the
uselessness of such a tool. :)

I thank in advance anyone reporting bugs dued to fIXnICE patches or programs
that doesn't like to be niced or rescheduled.
I would also be happy to support anyone proposing a new interesting feature to
improve scheduling quality through fIXnICE.

Look at the @{" contacts " link CONTACTS} page for my e-mail address.
@endnode


@node BUGS " Known bugs "

@{b}@{u} Known bugs @{ub}@{uu}

May sound lame (and probably it is), but fIXnICE, since its early version, has
few known bugs, which I haven't been able neither to fix nor to understand why
they occur.
A first thought led me to blame the authors of those programs, but, who knows,
maybe it's my fault.
What is sure is that the only thing a bit "nasty" fIXnICE does is patching 2
exec library vectors (SetTaskPri() and AddTask()), and I noticed that launching
fIXnICE with the parameter @{" NOPATCH " link USAGE} no bugs occur.
The following programs generate 680x0 exceptions (that is guru, if you don't
use MCP), but don't crashes the system (you can suspend the process and
everything will be fine):

 - @{b}CrossDOSFileSystem@{ub}
   As soon as PC0: is mounted, "PC0" process generates a Line-F emulation
   exception (vector 0xB).

 - @{b}ppc.library@{ub}
   The first program that tries to start the PowerPC kernel (such as ElfLoadSeg)
   makes one of the 68k-side handler processes die.
   In particular, the "CTRLHandler" process generates a Privilege Violation
   exception (vector 6).
   Notice that WarpOS kernel (which is far much better), works perfectly
   with fIXnICE, and it creates "Defiant" and "Babylon" processes on the 68k
   side in the same way.


Seems like crashes occur when calling AddTask(), since both the programs try to
create new tasks/processes and it's there where they fail.
The question is: do only these two programs create new processes ? And the
others, why don't they crash ?
This is the reason why I almost think it's not my fault...
But what should be the reason ? What could they do so dirty to make AddTask()
crash ?
I have an hypothesis: the new AddTask() function (fIXnICE one, I mean) connects
to Executive server to force a nice value to the just-born task: both the
connection, the nice calulation and other stuff obviously take some more stack
space. If the father process just fits in its stack space, there won't be enough
room for 2 more calls.
If this is the case, I wonder why there are still coders who are not able to
add some stack to their programs (it's also well written in the RKM).


@{b}NOTE@{ub}: My system is an Amiga 4000 with a CyberStormPPC 060/50 + 604e/200 and
      an Ultra-Wide-SCSI HD connected to the controller on it.
      32 MB EDO-RAM 60ns installed on the PowerUp board.
      No gfx card, no audio card.
      Test if the same troubles occur on other systems.
      

@endnode


@node COPYRIGHT " Copyright and Distribution "

@{b}@{u} Copyright (or supposed to) @{ub}@{uu}

I really don't know a damned thing about legal stuff, etc. The only thing I
know is that fIXnICE is free but it's basically a client of a shareware program
(Executive by Petri Nordlund). And the worst thing is that, patching exec
library, it makes a commercial OS and any application running clients of a
shareware program... I'll surely end up in clink :)

Anyway you need Executive to run fIXnICE, either the demo version or the full
registered version (the latter would be much more better, since fIXnICE is
designed to work at its best with a feedback rescheduling algorithm).
I know I should not be the one telling you that, but consider registering to
Executive (I tried but the author seems not to answer to e-mails, maybe he left
Amiga ages ago and he doesn't mind Executive at all) since it's probably the
best program ever written, and should be considered by everybody as part of the
kernel.


@{b}@{u} Distribution @{ub}@{uu}

You can spread fIXnICE where you like, but remember to spread also this guide
with it, at least because it's quite hard to use without.
And, please, don't try to modify the archive.

@endnode

